body:
Please ensure you have given all the following requested information in your report.
#### Issue details

When attempting to make a completely transparent cursor (to effectively hide the system default), I noticed it comes out black unless the size is over 8*8.
#### Reproduction steps/code

```
Pixmap pm = new Pixmap(8,8,Format.RGBA8888); 
Pixmap.setBlending(Pixmap.Blending.None); 
pm.setColor(Color.CLEAR);
pm.fillRectangle(0, 0, 8, 8);  
Gdx.graphics.setCursor(Gdx.graphics.newCursor(pm, 0, 0));
```
#### Barebones desktop application;

```
public class Barebones extends ApplicationAdapter {

    public void create () {

        //set cursor transparent test
        Pixmap pm = new Pixmap(8,8,Format.RGBA8888); //16x16 works.  8x8 does not.
        Pixmap.setBlending(Pixmap.Blending.None); //ensure when we draw transparent we REPLACE the pixels with a transparent color.
        pm.setColor(0f,0f,0f,0f);
        pm.fillRectangle(0, 0, 8, 8); //16x16 works.  8x8 does not.
        Gdx.graphics.setCursor(Gdx.graphics.newCursor(pm, 0, 0));
        //--------------------------
    }

    public void render () {
        Gdx.gl.glClearColor(1, 0, 0, 1);
        Gdx.gl.glClear(GL20.GL_COLOR_BUFFER_BIT);
    }

    public static void main (String[] args) throws Exception {
        new LwjglApplication(new Barebones());
    }
}

```

With the above code, the cursor gets set to a black square.
If, however, the size of the pixmap and fill is set to 16x16, the result is the cursor is set transparent as you'd expect.
Not sure if the problem is with the fill or the newCursor.
#### Version of LibGDX and/or relevant dependencies

Applies at least to;
1.7.2
1.9.4
#### Please select the affected platforms
- Tested on Windows 10 desktop.
#### New observations;

I noticed that when using a 8x8 pixmap it in fact produces a horizontal black _rectangle_. (4x8 I think). I said square earlier, this was wrong.
The rectangle might imply the fill function is half working ? replacing the lower pixels with transparent but not the top?
